&gt;&gt; Roberta I.

00:00:20.060 --> 00:00:21.530
Shaffer: I think we'll
go ahead and get started

00:00:21.530 --> 00:00:25.630
because under the conditions
of commuting

00:00:25.630 --> 00:00:28.880
into this city this morning,
it's really impossible to predict

00:00:28.880 --> 00:00:34.480
when people might arrive and
what their voyage will be like.

00:00:34.480 --> 00:00:41.110 position:56%
It's my pleasure to welcome you this
morning to the 265th celebration

00:00:41.110 --> 00:00:43.230
of James Madison's birthday.

00:00:43.230 --> 00:00:47.790
My name is Roberta Shaffer and I
have the pleasure and privilege

00:00:47.790 --> 00:00:51.420
of serving as the Law
Librarian of Congress.

00:00:51.420 --> 00:00:56.180 position:56%
This building that we are in is with
James Madison Memorial Building.

00:00:56.180 --> 00:01:01.690
It is the only memorial to
James Madison in Washington,

00:01:01.690 --> 00:01:05.890
and I'm going to argue that it
is the most appropriate memorial

00:01:05.890 --> 00:01:08.240
possible to James Madison.

00:01:08.240 --> 00:01:11.180
And here are my reasons.

00:01:11.180 --> 00:01:15.830
First, even though Thomas
Jefferson gets all the credit,

00:01:15.830 --> 00:01:20.390
I think James Madison was
himself a huge fan of books,

00:01:20.390 --> 00:01:23.580
a bibliophile if I may say.

00:01:23.580 --> 00:01:28.160
He had a large collection
at his estate in Montpelier.

00:01:28.160 --> 00:01:31.050
And when he died, he
was very concerned

00:01:31.050 --> 00:01:33.040
about where his books would go.

00:01:33.040 --> 00:01:39.870 position:56%
So in my view, that qualifies you as
a lover of books and a bibliophile.

00:01:39.870 --> 00:01:43.850
It's also appropriate that
a building for the Library

00:01:43.850 --> 00:01:47.100
of Congress be named for
Madison because he served

00:01:47.100 --> 00:01:52.540
in numerous positions in government
and of course had a huge influence

00:01:52.540 --> 00:01:56.400
on the very form of
government that we have enjoyed

00:01:56.400 --> 00:01:58.720
for all these many years.

00:01:58.720 --> 00:02:03.900
The statue that is in Memorial Hall
on the very first floor as you come

00:02:03.900 --> 00:02:08.650
into the building has-- depicts
James Madison holding a book

00:02:08.650 --> 00:02:14.210
and it is an encyclopedia, a
French encyclopedia, nonetheless,

00:02:14.210 --> 00:02:18.290
but an encyclopedia that
covers all subject matters.

00:02:18.290 --> 00:02:22.020
So, he is memorialized
in his Memorial Building

00:02:22.020 --> 00:02:25.820
with a block in his marble hand.

00:02:25.820 --> 00:02:28.740
But the last reason I
think it's appropriate

00:02:28.740 --> 00:02:33.130
that James Madison have a
building that's part of the Library

00:02:33.130 --> 00:02:36.500
of Congress footprint
named for him is

00:02:36.500 --> 00:02:42.320 position:56%
because I think he really understood
the idea of America's library.

00:02:42.320 --> 00:02:45.620
So anybody who has ever
worked at the Library

00:02:45.620 --> 00:02:49.280
of Congress knows two
quotes by heart.

00:02:49.280 --> 00:02:53.470
In fact, I think you have to
recite them after one week of work.

00:02:53.470 --> 00:02:58.200
And these are two quotes by
Thomas Jefferson, the first,

00:02:58.200 --> 00:03:00.770
"I cannot live without books."

00:03:00.770 --> 00:03:05.490
And most of us who work here share
that very philosophy and passion.

00:03:05.490 --> 00:03:11.140
And the second is that there
is no discipline or book

00:03:11.140 --> 00:03:15.580
for which Congress might
not have a need to refer.

00:03:15.580 --> 00:03:20.100
And that's a big paraphrase, but
it's something along those lines

00:03:20.100 --> 00:03:23.230
that Congress needs
universal knowledge.

00:03:23.230 --> 00:03:28.270
But there is a quote by
Madison that I think talks

00:03:28.270 --> 00:03:30.790
in a little bit different
way about the need

00:03:30.790 --> 00:03:34.790
for America's library
or a national library.

00:03:34.790 --> 00:03:36.960
And I'm probably going
to paraphrase it,

00:03:36.960 --> 00:03:38.780
and I just wrote it down quickly.

00:03:38.780 --> 00:03:41.570
But I'm sure I don't
have it by heart.

00:03:41.570 --> 00:03:43.430
But it goes along the lines

00:03:43.430 --> 00:03:49.550
of "Knowledge shall forever govern
ignorance, and people who mean

00:03:49.550 --> 00:03:53.580
to be their own governors
must arm themselves

00:03:53.580 --> 00:03:56.120
with the power of knowledge."

00:03:56.120 --> 00:04:00.080
And this quote or something
very close to it is enshrined

00:04:00.080 --> 00:04:02.550
at the very entrance
to our building,

00:04:02.550 --> 00:04:04.640
on the outside of the building.

00:04:04.640 --> 00:04:09.040
And to me, that speaks to
giving the people a library

00:04:09.040 --> 00:04:10.670
and not just Congress.

00:04:10.670 --> 00:04:16.480
So, that is my argument for why it
is so appropriate for James Madison

00:04:16.480 --> 00:04:21.280
to have this building named for him
and why we're so delighted today

00:04:21.280 --> 00:04:25.880
that you are joining us to
celebrate what would have been his

00:04:25.880 --> 00:04:27.330
265th birthday.

00:04:27.330 --> 00:04:31.860 position:56%
And who knows if he was a man of our
times with all of the biotechnology,

00:04:31.860 --> 00:04:37.650
he might very well be celebrating
here with us his 265th birthday.

