00:09:50.500 --> 00:09:53.360
Have they ceased that now?

00:09:53.360 --> 00:09:56.090 position:56%
Yeah. But it holds about 300 people.

00:09:56.090 --> 00:10:00.070
It has a wonderful view
of-- towards the airport.

00:10:00.070 --> 00:10:05.240
And-- So, that's also a small
gesture on Madison's behalf.

00:10:05.240 --> 00:10:14.470
He died in 1836 of course, and
the family was always needy.

00:10:14.470 --> 00:10:19.830
John Payne plays into
this immediate--

00:10:19.830 --> 00:10:24.470
that's the stepson who virtually
bankrupted Madison I suppose

00:10:24.470 --> 00:10:26.630
with his spending habits.

00:10:26.630 --> 00:10:30.550
But Dolley sold some
of the collection

00:10:30.550 --> 00:10:34.680
to Congress at 1837 and 1848.

00:10:34.680 --> 00:10:39.020
The 1837 sale, I'm going to say
very little more about that,

00:10:39.020 --> 00:10:44.400
but that did contain Madison's
notes, which we now have--

00:10:44.400 --> 00:10:46.690
is one of our great treasures.

00:10:46.690 --> 00:10:50.650
It's-- We have a group of things
here called top treasures among

00:10:50.650 --> 00:10:53.960
other, the Gettysburg Address,
Lincoln's Second Inaugural,

00:10:53.960 --> 00:10:56.670
the rough draft of the
Declaration of Independence.

00:10:56.670 --> 00:11:00.490
All of which are very
carefully preserved in a--

00:11:00.490 --> 00:11:05.770
deep in the bowels of
the library, in a safe--

00:11:05.770 --> 00:11:09.140
they're-- we hope they're secure.

00:11:09.140 --> 00:11:13.320
But the-- No, I mean at one point,
we were thinking of moving them

00:11:13.320 --> 00:11:17.340
to Fort Knox actually,
and did not do that.

00:11:17.340 --> 00:11:19.310
That was after 9/11.

00:11:19.310 --> 00:11:24.860
But they're-- So, they're still
here, Professor Bilder saw those.

00:11:24.860 --> 00:11:29.450
We do let people look at
them if they can convince us

00:11:29.450 --> 00:11:31.870
that they have a really need.

00:11:31.870 --> 00:11:33.580
Generally-- That's true.

00:11:33.580 --> 00:11:38.330
Most kind of valuable manuscripts
are on the library if for instance

00:11:38.330 --> 00:11:40.570
in the Manuscript Division, if
you walk in there and wanted

00:11:40.570 --> 00:11:44.240
to see Madison's papers, we
would ask you or anybody else is

00:11:44.240 --> 00:11:47.270
that we film-- you'd have to use
a microfilm, nobody likes that.

00:11:47.270 --> 00:11:51.930
And I get a constant stream of
people coming over and say, well,

00:11:51.930 --> 00:11:53.800
you know, I can't-- you
know, I can't use this,

00:11:53.800 --> 00:11:55.100
couldn't I see the original.

00:11:55.100 --> 00:11:57.050
But-- And generally,
we'll let people--

00:11:57.050 --> 00:12:02.050
if people are doing handwriting
analysis or looking at inks

00:12:02.050 --> 00:12:04.210
and so forth, we'll
let them look at that.

00:12:04.210 --> 00:12:05.930
And we will let somebody--

00:12:05.930 --> 00:12:09.980
I mean, she's not the first
person who's ever seen this.

00:12:09.980 --> 00:12:13.400
And so, we will let people
see some of these treasures.

00:12:13.400 --> 00:12:18.650
But they have other-- I mean to put
them on an exhibit, you have to--

00:12:18.650 --> 00:12:22.380
there has to be an armed
guard and that kind of thing.

00:12:22.380 --> 00:12:28.190
So-- But in any case, the 1837
sale did contain the notes.

00:12:28.190 --> 00:12:35.450
And I'll leave that alone and not
talk about the nature of the notes,

00:12:35.450 --> 00:12:39.450
which has been a kind of
a subject of [inaudible],

00:12:39.450 --> 00:12:43.340
isn't he the first one
who accused Madison

00:12:43.340 --> 00:12:46.010
for forging the note so to speak?

00:12:46.010 --> 00:12:47.520
[ Inaudible Remark ]

00:12:47.520 --> 00:12:48.960
Hamilton [inaudible], OK.

00:12:48.960 --> 00:12:51.290
But there's a long--
there's a history of this.

00:12:51.290 --> 00:12:54.180
Yeah. Yeah.

00:12:54.180 --> 00:13:02.010
OK. So, Congress got some papers at
1837 and 1848 and treated these--

00:13:02.010 --> 00:13:05.210
and generally, the 19th century
didn't seem not to have much

00:13:05.210 --> 00:13:08.240
of an appreciation, at
least custodians were,

00:13:08.240 --> 00:13:12.150
the sanctity of what we might call,
you know, important manuscripts.

00:13:12.150 --> 00:13:16.170
Congress lent some of the stuff
out to William Cabell Rives,

00:13:16.170 --> 00:13:18.950
a biographer, I guess just
sort of handed them over.

00:13:18.950 --> 00:13:23.760
I mean, Rives was Madison's first
biographer or first-- that's not--

00:13:23.760 --> 00:13:26.770
maybe not true, but
he was well-connected.

00:13:26.770 --> 00:13:30.340
So, he got substantial
number of papers.

00:13:30.340 --> 00:13:33.360
Eventually, they were returned by
a relative and they're called--

00:13:33.360 --> 00:13:34.660
we call those the Rives's--

00:13:34.660 --> 00:13:37.720
that's the Rives's section
of the Madison Papers.

00:13:37.720 --> 00:13:40.570
But I-- Apparently,
Rives did not turn--

00:13:40.570 --> 00:13:46.530
Rives's representatives did not
return everything, something.

00:13:46.530 --> 00:13:52.530
So, we have those papers
leaving and some not returning.

00:13:52.530 --> 00:13:57.420
And then John Todd Payne of course
who was always broke, and Madison--

00:13:57.420 --> 00:14:02.220
he almost bankrupted Madison,
didn't he, supporting the guy.

00:14:02.220 --> 00:14:04.070
Well, he sold some of them off.

00:14:04.070 --> 00:14:08.440
Really, he sold some of them
off to a man named McGuire,

00:14:08.440 --> 00:14:15.450
a lot of them off actually,
something about 2900 of them.

00:14:15.450 --> 00:14:21.990
McGuire kept them, at his
death, I believe in 1892,

00:14:21.990 --> 00:14:26.360
they were auctioned, some of
them, most of them and bought

00:14:26.360 --> 00:14:31.970
by Walter Benjamin, a important
manuscript collector at that point.

00:14:31.970 --> 00:14:35.110
He sold them to the
Chicago Historical Society,

00:14:35.110 --> 00:14:40.100 position:56%
and the library bought them back
from the Chicago Historical Society.

00:14:40.100 --> 00:14:47.430
In 1905-- So we got those back.

00:14:47.430 --> 00:14:50.220
That's-- That-- It was
after, however, in 19--

00:14:50.220 --> 00:14:54.690
that the State Department in
the 19th century was the keeper

00:14:54.690 --> 00:14:58.280
of government manuscripts,
not the Library of Congress.

00:14:58.280 --> 00:14:59.660
The library didn't have room.

00:14:59.660 --> 00:15:01.600
You've seen-- Some of you
may have seen some pictures

00:15:01.600 --> 00:15:04.390
of the library just
overwhelmed by paper.

00:15:04.390 --> 00:15:06.210
But the State Department was the--

00:15:06.210 --> 00:15:13.310
that was the National Archives
until 1903 when the government--

00:15:13.310 --> 00:15:17.320
I don't know, John
Cole I think is out.

00:15:17.320 --> 00:15:21.820
Was a law passed or was it just an
executive order ordering the State

00:15:21.820 --> 00:15:24.610
Department to return
whatever archives it had

00:15:24.610 --> 00:15:27.190
over to the Library of Congress.

00:15:27.190 --> 00:15:28.490
&gt;&gt; Executive--

00:15:28.490 --> 00:15:29.790
&gt;&gt; James Hutson: I think
it was an executive order.

00:15:29.790 --> 00:15:31.660
So, that-- that's how we got--

00:15:31.660 --> 00:15:37.250 position:56%
that's how the library really got
the-- most of our great manuscript--

00:15:37.250 --> 00:15:41.310
Washington, Jefferson and others.

00:15:41.310 --> 00:15:44.430
The State Department turned--
Because it didn't have any room

00:15:44.430 --> 00:15:46.540
and we just moved into
a large empty building

00:15:46.540 --> 00:15:50.090
in 1897, the Jefferson Building.

00:15:50.090 --> 00:15:55.450 position:56%
So, that really was the basis of the
Manuscript Division and the source

00:15:55.450 --> 00:15:57.570
of our-- some of our
greatest collections.

00:15:57.570 --> 00:16:04.680
So in 1905, the State Department
turned over such Madison Papers

00:16:04.680 --> 00:16:10.590
out of its hand, and that
was about 8600 items.

00:16:10.590 --> 00:16:13.700
We did, as I say, buy
back those things

00:16:13.700 --> 00:16:15.260
and most of them went to McGuire.

00:16:15.260 --> 00:16:17.940
That was about 2,900.

00:16:17.940 --> 00:16:23.010
And over the years, we've acquired
more by gifts and purchases.

