00:24:58.570 --> 00:25:05.230 position:56%
and done was taken down with a labor
and exactness beyond comprehension."

00:25:05.230 --> 00:25:08.180
And Jefferson wrote that,
"It was the ablest work

00:25:08.180 --> 00:25:12.680
of this kind ever yet executed."

00:25:12.680 --> 00:25:15.700
And Adams says, I will
unlikely not live to see it.

00:25:15.700 --> 00:25:17.850
And that was true,
both he and Jefferson

00:25:17.850 --> 00:25:20.670
of course died on July 4th.

00:25:20.670 --> 00:25:24.160
Ten years-- 11 years later in 1826.

00:25:24.160 --> 00:25:27.980
And to Jefferson, Madison seemed
the consummate, notetaker.

00:25:27.980 --> 00:25:30.500
But the reality is
somewhat different.

00:25:30.500 --> 00:25:34.140
Madison's most significant
and lasting contribution

00:25:34.140 --> 00:25:37.500
to the convention is
perhaps his notes.

00:25:37.500 --> 00:25:40.030
And this record of the
convention usually referred

00:25:40.030 --> 00:25:44.570
to as Madison's notes are the most
complete and detailed description

00:25:44.570 --> 00:25:46.280
of the Constitutional Convention.

00:25:46.280 --> 00:25:49.120
An official record of the
convention was compiled

00:25:49.120 --> 00:25:54.840 position:56%
by Secretary William Jackson, the
National Archives holds that record,

00:25:54.840 --> 00:25:58.840
and notes also survived
from 10 other delegates.

00:25:58.840 --> 00:26:02.140
But Madison's notes are the
only ones that cover every day

00:26:02.140 --> 00:26:04.600
of the convention,
beginning on May 14th

00:26:04.600 --> 00:26:07.910
and ending on September 17th 1787.

00:26:07.910 --> 00:26:10.530
And no other notes are as long.

00:26:10.530 --> 00:26:16.240
The manuscripts comprise of
136 and a half sheets of paper,

00:26:16.240 --> 00:26:19.270
folded in half, and he wrote on big
sheets, and they fold it in half,

00:26:19.270 --> 00:26:20.640
with four pages of writing.

00:26:20.640 --> 00:26:23.840
He wrote on the front, opened it,
wrote on the second and third page,

00:26:23.840 --> 00:26:25.670
reversed it, wrote on the back.

00:26:25.670 --> 00:26:29.730
So, it's over 500 pages
of manuscript.

00:26:29.730 --> 00:26:33.210
And no other notes depict the
convention as Madison's notes do,

00:26:33.210 --> 00:26:37.260 position:56%
as a political drama with compelling
characters, lengthy discourses

00:26:37.260 --> 00:26:39.900
on political theories,
crushing disappointments

00:26:39.900 --> 00:26:42.240
and seeming miraculous successes.

00:26:42.240 --> 00:26:44.470
And the notes are, as the
library catalogues them,

00:26:44.470 --> 00:26:48.430
properly considered a top
treasure of the American people.

00:26:48.430 --> 00:26:51.030
But what kind of notetaker was he?

00:26:51.030 --> 00:26:54.210
The notes have often been relied
on as if they'd been taken

00:26:54.210 --> 00:26:58.140
by a court reporter or stenographer
for the Congressional record.

00:26:58.140 --> 00:26:59.980
But the original notes
were actually an example

00:26:59.980 --> 00:27:02.910
of a genre we might call
a legislative diary.

00:27:02.910 --> 00:27:08.130
In the 18th century, legislative
proceedings were closed,

00:27:08.130 --> 00:27:13.050
much like the deliberations of
judges and justices remain today.

00:27:13.050 --> 00:27:16.520
And we'll forgive anybody, who
at 11 o'clock needs to look

00:27:16.520 --> 00:27:20.330
at their phone, to find out who the
next Supreme Court justice nominee

00:27:20.330 --> 00:27:22.200
is going to be.

00:27:22.200 --> 00:27:26.460
What the public had a right to was
the final product, the legislation

00:27:26.460 --> 00:27:28.560
and the formal general
procedural motions.

00:27:28.560 --> 00:27:31.800 position:56%
Indeed, although the House of
Representatives would open its doors

00:27:31.800 --> 00:27:35.370
in 1789, the Senate
actually remained closed

00:27:35.370 --> 00:27:38.380
to the public until 1795.

00:27:38.380 --> 00:27:40.210
And without published
accounts of debates,

00:27:40.210 --> 00:27:43.240
legislators relied
on private diaries.

00:27:43.240 --> 00:27:45.780
So, Madison's notes at the
convention were taken for himself

00:27:45.780 --> 00:27:48.760
and likely Thomas Jefferson.

00:27:48.760 --> 00:27:51.260
Madison had taken similar
notes when he had served

00:27:51.260 --> 00:27:53.450
in the Confederation Congress

00:27:53.450 --> 00:27:55.920
and Madison had shared
these with Jefferson.

00:27:55.920 --> 00:27:59.270
Jefferson was in Paris since 1784,

00:27:59.270 --> 00:28:01.750
he will miss the convention
entirely.

00:28:01.750 --> 00:28:06.340
At the convention, Madison's
notes practiced political ideas,

00:28:06.340 --> 00:28:11.050
his strategies and the positions
of allies and opponents.

00:28:11.050 --> 00:28:13.450
And the original notes
reflected what he cared about

00:28:13.450 --> 00:28:16.130
and they omitted what he
did not find interesting.

00:28:16.130 --> 00:28:18.700
As past scholars, including
Jim Hutson,

00:28:18.700 --> 00:28:23.090
have estimated Madison's
notes contain only about 10%

00:28:23.090 --> 00:28:25.140
of what was likely
said at the convention.

00:28:25.140 --> 00:28:30.110
But that 10% related
almost entirely to Madison.

00:28:30.110 --> 00:28:33.970
Madison's notes were not a
contemporaneous complete account.

00:28:33.970 --> 00:28:36.700
Most likely twice a week,
on Wednesdays and Sundays

00:28:36.700 --> 00:28:38.990
when he did his other
correspondence,

00:28:38.990 --> 00:28:42.890
he wrote up rough notes that he
had taken during the proceedings.

00:28:42.890 --> 00:28:44.360
His rough notes were likely filled

00:28:44.360 --> 00:28:46.830
with abbreviations he
did not know shorthand.

00:28:46.830 --> 00:28:49.820
And the notes began as a fair copy

00:28:49.820 --> 00:28:53.640
of these no longer
extant rough notes.

00:28:53.640 --> 00:28:58.120
Thus in the notes, the
longest speeches appear usually

00:28:58.120 --> 00:29:00.230
in Saturday's notes.

00:29:00.230 --> 00:29:02.640
Not necessarily because they
were the most important,

00:29:02.640 --> 00:29:06.970
but because a Sundays without
meetings gave Madison time

00:29:06.970 --> 00:29:09.120
to decipher his rough notes.

00:29:09.120 --> 00:29:12.530
And when Madison wrote about
events that had happened on Monday

00:29:12.530 --> 00:29:16.020
or Thursday, he knew what
the convention had gone

00:29:16.020 --> 00:29:19.850 position:56%
on to decide in the succeeding days.

00:29:19.850 --> 00:29:23.400
These days therefore were
always written with hindsight.

00:29:23.400 --> 00:29:28.120
And so, from the first day, Madison
was revising his understanding.

00:29:28.120 --> 00:29:32.090
Now, I love talking about the notes
with law students because they know

00:29:32.090 --> 00:29:36.300
from firsthand experience that
one cannot take notes while one

00:29:36.300 --> 00:29:37.600
is speaking.

00:29:37.600 --> 00:29:40.440
In law schools, we still maintain,
particularly in the first year,

00:29:40.440 --> 00:29:44.600
the formal tradition of
spontaneously calling on people,

00:29:44.600 --> 00:29:47.190
Ms. Bilder, tell us about the case.

00:29:47.190 --> 00:29:50.420
And you now, at that
moment, your mind is blank.

00:29:50.420 --> 00:29:54.270
You cannot sit and try and answer
the question and write notes.

00:29:54.270 --> 00:29:57.400
When they're called on in class,
they either leave their notes blank

00:29:57.400 --> 00:30:01.170
or what they often do is they
compose that section later,

00:30:01.170 --> 00:30:05.110
reflecting what they realized
afterwards was the right answer.

00:30:05.110 --> 00:30:08.400 position:56%
And most of my students tell me that
in their notes, if they write them,

00:30:08.400 --> 00:30:12.350
they're filled with brilliance of
what they must have said in class.

00:30:12.350 --> 00:30:15.390
Madison's own speeches in
the notes are thus troubling

00:30:15.390 --> 00:30:17.360
in terms of reliability.

00:30:17.360 --> 00:30:20.310
Madison wrote what
he wished he'd said.

00:30:20.310 --> 00:30:24.550
Indeed, his famous June 19th speech
supporting the national Virginia

00:30:24.550 --> 00:30:27.870
Plan was recorded by a
number of other notetakers.

00:30:27.870 --> 00:30:31.390
And in their notes,
it's rather meandering.

00:30:31.390 --> 00:30:33.470
But in Madison note--
Madison's notes,

00:30:33.470 --> 00:30:39.070
it's a well-organized six-page
disquisition on political theory.

00:30:39.070 --> 00:30:41.490
Moreover, in the years
immediately after the convention,

00:30:41.490 --> 00:30:45.740
Madison likely replaced several of
the sheets containing his speeches.

00:30:45.740 --> 00:30:49.140
His motivation is unknowable,
but it may have been to clarify

00:30:49.140 --> 00:30:52.030
and expand arguments that he
made or to delete statements

00:30:52.030 --> 00:30:53.860
that he might have
been misunderstood

00:30:53.860 --> 00:30:56.500
in terms of later controversies.

00:30:56.500 --> 00:30:59.190
So now, let me, second talk
