several years after the convention

00:31:03.570 --> 00:31:08.260
with Jefferson, Madison Riley
referred to the naked eye

00:31:08.260 --> 00:31:11.060
of the ordinary politician.

00:31:11.060 --> 00:31:13.620
We don't always think of
Madison as a politician.

00:31:13.620 --> 00:31:15.870
Now, I think, David's
book does a wonderful job

00:31:15.870 --> 00:31:18.210
of emphasizing this aspect.

00:31:18.210 --> 00:31:21.760
And the original notes reflected
Madison's political aspirations.

00:31:21.760 --> 00:31:26.760
In them, he emerges as a
proactive political strategist.

00:31:26.760 --> 00:31:31.230
The original notes from June
to July 1787 are fixated

00:31:31.230 --> 00:31:34.130 position:56%
on Madison's almost obsessive desire

00:31:34.130 --> 00:31:37.070
to create a powerful
national government

00:31:37.070 --> 00:31:41.330
with proportional representation
in both houses.

00:31:41.330 --> 00:31:44.030
More than anything,
he wanted the states

00:31:44.030 --> 00:31:47.690
to lose their representation
in Congress.

00:31:47.690 --> 00:31:53.290
Madison came to the convention
desiring what he called the due

00:31:53.290 --> 00:32:00.360 position:56%
supremacy of the national authority
leaving the states, or as he put it,

00:32:00.360 --> 00:32:07.220
local authorities, as far as
they can be subordinately useful.

00:32:07.220 --> 00:32:11.210
OK. He wanted to end equality
of suffrage of the states.

00:32:11.210 --> 00:32:13.560
He wanted the national
government to have the power

00:32:13.560 --> 00:32:15.530
in cases requiring uniformity.

00:32:15.530 --> 00:32:19.050
He wanted the national
government to even have a negative,

00:32:19.050 --> 00:32:22.810
what we might now call
a veto, over state laws.

00:32:22.810 --> 00:32:26.500
He wanted the constitution to be
supreme to state constitutions.

00:32:26.500 --> 00:32:34.650
As he put it, he planned to strike
so deeply at the old confederation.

00:32:34.650 --> 00:32:39.510
Madison opposed completely and
thoroughly the federal compromised

00:32:39.510 --> 00:32:43.910
that Congress now embodies in which
the house represents population

00:32:43.910 --> 00:32:45.210
in the Senate-- the state.

00:32:45.210 --> 00:32:49.630
At first, Madison thought he
would succeed on June 13th.

00:32:49.630 --> 00:32:53.270
The convention prepared a committee
of the whole report in which many

00:32:53.270 --> 00:32:55.630
of Madison's hopes were realized.

00:32:55.630 --> 00:33:01.220
And in the notes, Madison recorded
this report on its own sheet.

00:33:01.220 --> 00:33:04.340
His handwriting is beautiful.

00:33:04.340 --> 00:33:06.580
It's carefully spaced.

00:33:06.580 --> 00:33:11.150
He left the last page blank.

00:33:11.150 --> 00:33:13.560
In the many revisions
of the manuscript,

00:33:13.560 --> 00:33:16.230
he never wrote on this blank page.

00:33:16.230 --> 00:33:18.700
Other places, he had to even
fill in little scrunchie things,

00:33:18.700 --> 00:33:20.300
he left that last page blank.

00:33:20.300 --> 00:33:24.300
Why? June 13th ended a
critical phase of the convention

00:33:24.300 --> 00:33:27.900
and never again would
Madison's vision and that

00:33:27.900 --> 00:33:30.950
of the majority aligned so closely.

00:33:30.950 --> 00:33:33.460
Now, those familiar with the
traditional narrative know

00:33:33.460 --> 00:33:34.760
what happened.

00:33:34.760 --> 00:33:37.530
The small states successfully
fought back.

00:33:37.530 --> 00:33:40.550
They worried about
future political dominance

00:33:40.550 --> 00:33:44.420
and the other two large states,
Massachusetts and Pennsylvania.

00:33:44.420 --> 00:33:49.250
Madison rejected repeated
suggestions that he compromise

00:33:49.250 --> 00:33:51.220
and permit one branch of Congress

00:33:51.220 --> 00:33:53.450
to reflect the equal
suffrage of the states.

00:33:53.450 --> 00:33:58.380
In the notes, he even recorded John
Dickinson warning him privately,

00:33:58.380 --> 00:34:02.450
"You see the consequences
of pushing things too far."

00:34:02.450 --> 00:34:05.820
Madison wrote down the advice,
and then ignored it completely.

00:34:05.820 --> 00:34:07.120
He dismissed it.

00:34:07.120 --> 00:34:11.780
It would be a fatal error not just
for Madison, but for the country.

00:34:11.780 --> 00:34:15.410 position:56%
Madison's commitment to ending
state representation in Congress was

00:34:15.410 --> 00:34:19.000
so strong that he came
up with a plan

00:34:19.000 --> 00:34:22.880
to persuade the three
southern states to join

00:34:22.880 --> 00:34:24.970
with the three large states.

00:34:24.970 --> 00:34:29.700
He repeatedly hinted at a
sectional division between northern

00:34:29.700 --> 00:34:32.430
and southern states over slavery.

00:34:32.430 --> 00:34:36.810
And Madison then proposed
a bicameral Congress based

00:34:36.810 --> 00:34:38.110
on this division.

00:34:38.110 --> 00:34:41.480
One branch would represent
free white inhabitants.

00:34:41.480 --> 00:34:47.110 position:56%
The other would represent all people
free and enslaved African-Americans.

00:34:47.110 --> 00:34:51.350
But enslaved African-Americans
of course would not vote.

00:34:51.350 --> 00:34:54.200
Madison's plan thus
gave voting power

00:34:54.200 --> 00:34:56.960
to states that legalized slavery.

00:34:56.960 --> 00:35:00.860
And Virginia, by this calculation,
would have benefited the most,

00:35:00.860 --> 00:35:03.930
it held nearly 300,000 people,

00:35:03.930 --> 00:35:09.190
enslaved nearly half the enslaved
population in the United States.

00:35:09.190 --> 00:35:12.020
Madison's idea was
never formally adopted.

00:35:12.020 --> 00:35:15.050
But his insistence on a
sectional division over slavery

00:35:15.050 --> 00:35:17.710
and his suggestion that
the slave states needed

00:35:17.710 --> 00:35:21.450
to protect their interests in the
national government instigated,

00:35:21.450 --> 00:35:23.530
I believe, the dynamic that led

00:35:23.530 --> 00:35:26.340
to five constitutional
provisions protecting slavery

00:35:26.340 --> 00:35:28.090
in the constitution.

00:35:28.090 --> 00:35:30.480
And although after
leaving the convention,

00:35:30.480 --> 00:35:33.880
Madison would blame South
Carolina and Georgia

00:35:33.880 --> 00:35:38.460
for what has been seen now as an
inevitable compromise over slavery.

00:35:38.460 --> 00:35:41.950
Madison was equally at fault.

00:35:41.950 --> 00:35:44.010
His willingness to embrace slavery

00:35:44.010 --> 00:35:47.500
in the constitution reflected his
personal compromise over slavery.

00:35:47.500 --> 00:35:51.550
He believed it to be against the
principles of the revolution,

00:35:51.550 --> 00:35:55.640
but he could not imagine a
multiracial American nation.

00:35:55.640 --> 00:35:58.750
He freed no one at his death.

00:35:58.750 --> 00:36:03.360
Indeed, his will left the
profits from the sale of the notes

00:36:03.360 --> 00:36:07.010
of the convention to the
American Colonization Society,

00:36:07.010 --> 00:36:11.040
a group dedicated to sending
freed African-Americans back

00:36:11.040 --> 00:36:14.120
to Africa specifically Liberia.

00:36:14.120 --> 00:36:17.500
Now, on July 14th, I
think fortunately for us,

00:36:17.500 --> 00:36:20.340
Madison lost his quest
to prevent the states

00:36:20.340 --> 00:36:22.750
from having equal representation
in one branch.

00:36:22.750 --> 00:36:25.790
And Madison was mad.

00:36:25.790 --> 00:36:29.070
On Monday, he recorded
failed efforts

00:36:29.070 --> 00:36:32.270
to resurrect proportional
representation in both branches.

00:36:32.270 --> 00:36:36.460
He writes of an early morning
meeting among the large states,

00:36:36.460 --> 00:36:38.270
nothing was accomplished.

00:36:38.270 --> 00:36:45.030
He complained, "The time was
wasted in vague conversation."

00:36:45.030 --> 00:36:46.480
Although in future years,

00:36:46.480 --> 00:36:48.970
he actually became reconciled
to American federalism.

00:36:48.970 --> 00:36:52.060
Initially, the loss was not
at all palatable to him.

00:36:52.060 --> 00:36:53.560
He was so mad.

00:36:53.560 --> 00:36:56.780
He went on to do something
he would later regret.

00:36:56.780 --> 00:37:02.980
A mid-disagreement over
the executive on July 17th,

00:37:02.980 --> 00:37:09.860
a motion was made from Virginia
for an executive on good behavior.

00:37:09.860 --> 00:37:14.210
That is an executive who would
serve for life without term limits,

00:37:14.210 --> 00:37:17.420
only dismissible through
impeachment.

00:37:17.420 --> 00:37:22.940
Madison and the Virginians joined
three other states to vote in favor

00:37:22.940 --> 00:37:28.120
of it, lifetime tenure
for the president.

00:37:28.120 --> 00:37:29.890
Whether or not you agree with
that, it depends on whether

00:37:29.890 --> 00:37:31.510
or not you like the president.

00:37:31.510 --> 00:37:35.060
The vote was likely actually
aimed at emphasizing the need

00:37:35.060 --> 00:37:38.080
for the executive to have
free agency from the states,

00:37:38.080 --> 00:37:42.040
but the vote would haunt
Madison after the convention.

00:37:42.040 --> 00:37:44.500
It looked like Madison had voted

00:37:44.500 --> 00:37:47.880
for a secret monarchical
national government.

00:37:47.880 --> 00:37:52.640 position:56%
And this sheet in the note is one he
replaces and then repeatedly tries

00:37:52.640 --> 00:37:57.560
to explain by adding footnotes
along the side and up the margins,

00:37:57.560 --> 00:38:02.320
it's the sheet that's most
marked up in the actual note.

00:38:02.320 --> 00:38:05.510
So now, let me talk about
Madison, the drafter.

00:38:05.510 --> 00:38:10.590
On July 18th, after this vote,
Madison wrote Jefferson referring

00:38:10.590 --> 00:38:13.410 position:56%
to the drudgery of taking his notes.

00:38:13.410 --> 00:38:19.320
On July 18th, Madison was just
depressed beyond all anything.

00:38:19.320 --> 00:38:22.430
But ironically, it was his
notes that would save him.

00:38:22.430 --> 00:38:26.300
In fact, if Madison had quit
taking notes on July 17th,

00:38:26.300 --> 00:38:28.840
we would have only his
account of his failures

00:38:28.840 --> 00:38:32.650
and he might have been a permanent
outcast at the convention.

00:38:32.650 --> 00:38:36.550
But gradually, Madison emerged from
defeat and failure into a new role.

00:38:36.550 --> 00:38:39.450
He became a constructive
participant and was chosen

00:38:39.450 --> 00:38:41.950
for the most important committees.

00:38:41.950 --> 00:38:44.430
Initially, Madison
was such an outcast

00:38:44.430 --> 00:38:49.460
because of his adamant stances
for bicameral representation--

00:38:49.460 --> 00:38:51.290
bicameral proportional
representation

00:38:51.290 --> 00:38:54.630
that he wasn't even elected to
the first drafting committee,

00:38:54.630 --> 00:38:56.690
Randolph was elected instead.

00:38:56.690 --> 00:38:59.940
And after the drafting
committee came back,

00:38:59.940 --> 00:39:01.870
each member was given
a printed draft.

00:39:01.870 --> 00:39:05.420
And unlike everyone else at
the convention, Madison copied

00:39:05.420 --> 00:39:08.920
in hand the first draft
over into his notes.

00:39:08.920 --> 00:39:12.930
This process of copying gave
him an intimate familiarity

00:39:12.930 --> 00:39:15.570
with the structure,
language and substance.

00:39:15.570 --> 00:39:17.030
He noticed every word.

00:39:17.030 --> 00:39:20.410
He even noticed that the
printer had made an error

00:39:20.410 --> 00:39:25.730 position:56%
in writing Roman numeral sixth above
both the sixth and seventh articles.

00:39:25.730 --> 00:39:28.470
So, he knew the draft as
well as anyone who had served

00:39:28.470 --> 00:39:32.210
on the committee and
he had no stake in it.

00:39:32.210 --> 00:39:35.000
Madison's notes, now
rougher and more erratic,

00:39:35.000 --> 00:39:38.750
reflected Madison's fascination
with the drafting process.

00:39:38.750 --> 00:39:40.460
He loved drafting.

00:39:40.460 --> 00:39:42.790
He had loved it in the
Virginia Legislature.

00:39:42.790 --> 00:39:46.540
He loved words and the
struggle to find the right word.

00:39:46.540 --> 00:39:49.800 position:56%
And now in the convention, he turned
out to have a talent for working

00:39:49.800 --> 00:39:54.250
out semantic compromises that
sidestep theoretical disputes.

00:39:54.250 --> 00:39:58.280
He found himself proposing textual
changes or he was often able

00:39:58.280 --> 00:40:00.920
to point to a later
provision in the draft

00:40:00.920 --> 00:40:04.850
that resolved a seemingly
intractable issue.

00:40:04.850 --> 00:40:08.170
Madison was thoughtful on questions
about which matters belonged

00:40:08.170 --> 00:40:11.860
on a constitution and which
would be more appropriately left

00:40:11.860 --> 00:40:14.520
to ordinary legislative politics.

00:40:14.520 --> 00:40:17.810
And the notes reflected
his growing conviction

00:40:17.810 --> 00:40:23.040
that the constitution should
avoid unnecessary specifics.

00:40:23.040 --> 00:40:27.420 position:56%
By the third week of August, Madison
was rehabilitated in the eyes

00:40:27.420 --> 00:40:31.100
of the convention, no longer
was he the obsessed proponent

00:40:31.100 --> 00:40:33.640
of bicameral proportional
representation

00:40:33.640 --> 00:40:35.940
and a somewhat petulant loser.

00:40:35.940 --> 00:40:39.150
He had become a valued drafter.

00:40:39.150 --> 00:40:43.920
Now, the notes here reflect the
complexity of the drafting process.

00:40:43.920 --> 00:40:46.500
The delegates sent
controversial issues late

00:40:46.500 --> 00:40:48.270
in the convention to committees.

00:40:48.270 --> 00:40:51.620
In fact, there were six
committees between August 18th

00:40:51.620 --> 00:40:53.430
and the end of the convention.

00:40:53.430 --> 00:40:55.540
The increase in committee
work led the convention

00:40:55.540 --> 00:40:59.380
to change its adjournment
time from 4 p.m. to 3 to allow

00:40:59.380 --> 00:41:01.530
for all the committee work.

00:41:01.530 --> 00:41:05.460
In the last three and a half weeks
of the convention, Madison served

00:41:05.460 --> 00:41:08.870
on the three most important
committees, a committee dealing

00:41:08.870 --> 00:41:13.580
with slavery, a committee handling
everything that they had postponed

00:41:13.580 --> 00:41:16.700
like including everything
about the president as well

00:41:16.700 --> 00:41:18.810
as the five-men final
draft committee.

00:41:18.810 --> 00:41:24.310
And at this very moment, when
Madison was completely involved

00:41:24.310 --> 00:41:26.600
in the production of
the constitution,

00:41:26.600 --> 00:41:29.050
his original notes stopped.

00:41:29.050 --> 00:41:33.840
August 24th 1787 is the last
page of the original notes.

00:41:33.840 --> 00:41:36.660
And although there are notes for
the remaining weeks, I argue,

00:41:36.660 --> 00:41:41.460 position:56%
in the book that they were composed
two years later in the fall of 1789.

00:41:41.460 --> 00:41:44.150
This collapse of the
notes is not surprising.

00:41:44.150 --> 00:41:46.940
Madison had little time
given his committee work.

00:41:46.940 --> 00:41:48.700
In fact, if you chart
out his committee work,

00:41:48.700 --> 00:41:50.810
there's literally almost no day

00:41:50.810 --> 00:41:53.370
on which he could have
written his rough notes up.

00:41:53.370 --> 00:41:55.310
And moreover, he became sick,

00:41:55.310 --> 00:41:58.520
something that he was
susceptible to under stress.

00:41:58.520 --> 00:42:02.510
And most importantly,
he was too involved

00:42:02.510 --> 00:42:06.050
with drafting the constitution
to bother with notes.

00:42:06.050 --> 00:42:11.430 position:56%
And I think he could not keep
distinct decisions made in committee

00:42:11.430 --> 00:42:12.770
with those in the convention.

00:42:12.770 --> 00:42:16.600
Thus, at the very moment, when
the convention decided many

00:42:16.600 --> 00:42:20.770
of the issues we debate today,
certain Congressional powers,

00:42:20.770 --> 00:42:24.640
impeachment, the vice
president, the Electoral College,

00:42:24.640 --> 00:42:28.360
all the presidential powers and
the grouping and relationships

00:42:28.360 --> 00:42:33.290
that converted the 23 final
articles into our seven,

00:42:33.290 --> 00:42:36.250
the notes are the most unreliable.

00:42:36.250 --> 00:42:41.800 position:56%
But this collapse of the notes
reflected the contemporary inability

00:42:41.800 --> 00:42:47.860
of Madison and all the delegates
to see the final constitution

00:42:47.860 --> 00:42:51.420
in the sense that we
mistakenly imagine they could.

00:42:51.420 --> 00:42:54.950
The collapse of the notes means
that Madison's great successes

00:42:54.950 --> 00:42:58.640
in the final weeks
are invisible to us.

00:42:58.640 --> 00:43:02.330
So finally, let me talk
about Madison the reviser.

00:43:02.330 --> 00:43:07.220
Two years would pass before
Madison composed the final weeks

00:43:07.220 --> 00:43:08.520
of the notes.

00:43:08.520 --> 00:43:12.770
And by then, his rough notes were
undoubtedly difficult to decipher.

00:43:12.770 --> 00:43:15.740
And moreover, in the intervening
two years; the convention had begun

00:43:15.740 --> 00:43:18.210
to acquire a different
set of meanings.

00:43:18.210 --> 00:43:20.940
In fact, as a member
of the First Congress,

00:43:20.940 --> 00:43:24.630
Madison had repeatedly
confronted the difficulties

00:43:24.630 --> 00:43:27.190
of interpreting the constitution.

00:43:27.190 --> 00:43:29.970
In addition, he'd champion
the successful amendment

00:43:29.970 --> 00:43:32.250
of the constitution
with 12 amendments,

00:43:32.250 --> 00:43:35.960
the ratified 10 we know
today as the Bill of Rights.

00:43:35.960 --> 00:43:40.500
Significantly, Congress's
decision to add rather

00:43:40.500 --> 00:43:44.590
than interweave those
amendments made the constitution

00:43:44.590 --> 00:43:46.580
and the conventions work

00:43:46.580 --> 00:43:51.610
for the first time begin
to be seen as sacred.

00:43:51.610 --> 00:43:56.300
In the fall of 1789, Jefferson
was expected to return from Paris.

00:43:56.300 --> 00:43:59.220
And Madison decided
to finish his notes.

00:43:59.220 --> 00:44:02.180
He secretly acquired
the official journal

00:44:02.180 --> 00:44:04.500
of the convention from
George Washington.

00:44:04.500 --> 00:44:12.580 position:56%
And George Washington's diary that
would have recorded this is missing.

00:44:12.580 --> 00:44:15.080
OK. Madison made a copy

00:44:15.080 --> 00:44:18.740
of the entire convention
journal, Yale holds that copy.

00:44:18.740 --> 00:44:22.040
And then he used this journal
copy to reconstruct the notes.

00:44:22.040 --> 00:44:26.330
He interspersed the official record
of the proceedings with remnants

00:44:26.330 --> 00:44:29.810
of speeches from whatever remaining
rough notes he had in his memory.

00:44:29.810 --> 00:44:33.570 position:56%
And then, Madison went back over the
first part of his notes and he began

00:44:33.570 --> 00:44:36.310
to add in more material from
the journal to alter words

00:44:36.310 --> 00:44:38.250
and phrases here and there.

00:44:38.250 --> 00:44:41.650
He even substituted three
sheets in early June

00:44:41.650 --> 00:44:45.770
to replace earlier unsatisfactory
versions of his speeches.

00:44:45.770 --> 00:44:50.230
After Jefferson returned, Madison
continued to revise his notes.

00:44:50.230 --> 00:44:53.630
Jefferson became obsessed
that Hamilton

00:44:53.630 --> 00:44:58.640 position:56%
and his allies were secretly devoted
to a more monarchical government.

00:44:58.640 --> 00:45:02.950
And this devotion had begun at the
convention, Jefferson believed.

00:45:02.950 --> 00:45:07.430
In the early 1790's,
Madison replaced five sheets.

00:45:07.430 --> 00:45:12.480
Each containing a speech or
vote capable of being read

00:45:12.480 --> 00:45:16.750
as Madison aligned with Hamilton.

00:45:16.750 --> 00:45:20.330
Now, you probably wish as he was
given Hamilton is like making

00:45:20.330 --> 00:45:23.010
in a 900-dollar tickets, OK.

00:45:23.010 --> 00:45:25.490
I haven't seen it.

00:45:25.490 --> 00:45:28.150
Madison could not completely
rewrite his speeches

00:45:28.150 --> 00:45:31.340
or pretend he had not spoken,
too many members remained alive,

00:45:31.340 --> 00:45:33.750
many with notes, but you
could ensure that sentences

00:45:33.750 --> 00:45:38.390
in his own handwriting would not
be used as evidence against them.

00:45:38.390 --> 00:45:40.650
In comparing other
versions of his speeches,

00:45:40.650 --> 00:45:44.790
I speculate that Madison carefully
eliminated his most controversial

00:45:44.790 --> 00:45:46.960
conclusion and he also sprinkled

00:45:46.960 --> 00:45:51.400
in occasionally Jefferson's new
buzzword, Republican Government.

00:45:51.400 --> 00:45:54.330
And during these years, Madison
began to revise the notes

00:45:54.330 --> 00:45:56.770
to convert his diary
into a record of debates.

00:45:56.770 --> 00:46:01.080
And along the way, he converted
himself into a different Madison.

00:46:01.080 --> 00:46:05.690
In the original notes, he's
caddy, grumpy and annoyed.

00:46:05.690 --> 00:46:08.060
But by altering a word
here, a phrase there,

00:46:08.060 --> 00:46:11.610
he became the moderate
dispassionate observer,

00:46:11.610 --> 00:46:14.060
thoughtful intellectual founder,

00:46:14.060 --> 00:46:18.520
future statue downstairs,
right, person.

00:46:18.520 --> 00:46:22.250
He revised concepts, terms,
narrowed general statements,

00:46:22.250 --> 00:46:24.560
added caveats through--
in cross references.

00:46:24.560 --> 00:46:27.950
At times, his revisions
border on fussiness.

00:46:27.950 --> 00:46:30.890
And after retiring from
the presidency in 1817,

00:46:30.890 --> 00:46:33.490
Madison continued to
revise the notes.

00:46:33.490 --> 00:46:37.170
By this point, the Madison-- the
manuscript was covered in revisions

00:46:37.170 --> 00:46:41.600
in various shades of ink, some
even showing the shake and slant

00:46:41.600 --> 00:46:46.400
of his later years often
with small slips attached.

00:46:46.400 --> 00:46:49.650
Although he repeatedly flirted
with publication he refrained,

00:46:49.650 --> 00:46:53.080
he worried about other accounts.

00:46:53.080 --> 00:46:57.880
By 1829, Madison was finally
the only living member left

00:46:57.880 --> 00:47:01.700
and he settled on posthumous
publication.

00:47:01.700 --> 00:47:07.180
Only after his death were his
notes finally published in 1840.

00:47:07.180 --> 00:47:10.020
I believe that Madison
understood his revisions

00:47:10.020 --> 00:47:12.120
as repeated efforts
to create a record.

00:47:12.120 --> 00:47:16.830
His record of what he saw is
significant in the convention.

00:47:16.830 --> 00:47:20.590 position:56%
And yet, every revision increased
the distance between Madison's notes

00:47:20.590 --> 00:47:23.030
and the actual convention.

00:47:23.030 --> 00:47:26.060
As a narrative of the convention,

00:47:26.060 --> 00:47:30.700
Madison's notes emphasized his
inability and the other delegates

00:47:30.700 --> 00:47:33.760
to perceive the extraordinary
document

00:47:33.760 --> 00:47:36.450
that the constitution would become.

00:47:36.450 --> 00:47:39.670
And equally importantly,
the original notes

00:47:39.670 --> 00:47:43.430
of the convention reflect
Madison's inability

00:47:43.430 --> 00:47:47.820
to perceive the extraordinary
person that he would become.

00:47:47.820 --> 00:47:52.340
I think the Madison of
1787 would be astounded

00:47:52.340 --> 00:47:56.390
that over two centuries later,
we'd be celebrating his birthday.

00:47:56.390 --> 00:47:58.730
And so, happy birthday
James Madison.

