00:50:32.370 --> 00:50:38.080
OK. I became fascinated with
two facts about James Madison

00:50:38.080 --> 00:50:39.640
that led me to want
to write my book.

00:50:39.640 --> 00:50:43.420
The first is I really concluded
that he was just so central

00:50:43.420 --> 00:50:44.970
to the nation's founding.

00:50:44.970 --> 00:50:48.620
He was, in my view, the
second most important figure.

00:50:48.620 --> 00:50:50.220
Washington is above everybody.

00:50:50.220 --> 00:50:51.540
You can't touch Washington.

00:50:51.540 --> 00:50:53.840
You couldn't touch him
then and you can't still.

00:50:53.840 --> 00:50:55.810
Without him, I'm not
sure there is a country.

00:50:55.810 --> 00:50:58.630
But I do believe Madison is second.

00:50:58.630 --> 00:51:02.390
And let me just tick off the
list of his achievements.

00:51:02.390 --> 00:51:04.810
He would-- He and Hamilton
were central to the calling

00:51:04.810 --> 00:51:08.310
of the Constitutional
Convention in 1787 at a time

00:51:08.310 --> 00:51:12.530
when the nation really was drifting
arguably towards more anarchical

00:51:12.530 --> 00:51:15.670
or at least a fractured state.

00:51:15.670 --> 00:51:18.030
Of course, the writing of the
constitution, we've heard something

00:51:18.030 --> 00:51:21.340
of his involvement in
that and his notetaking.

00:51:21.340 --> 00:51:27.070 position:56%
The fight for ratification, he and
Hamilton write the Federalist Papers

00:51:27.070 --> 00:51:31.480
which are the best political
writing by any Americans ever.

00:51:31.480 --> 00:51:34.120
The battle for ratification itself,

00:51:34.120 --> 00:51:37.150
the political fight
he and Hamilton lead.

00:51:37.150 --> 00:51:40.350
He is the leading member of the
First Congress, often referred to,

00:51:40.350 --> 00:51:43.770
in that first year, as
Washington's prime minister.

00:51:43.770 --> 00:51:46.630
He writes the legislation
that creates the government.

00:51:46.630 --> 00:51:52.270
He writes the Bill of Rights
and fights for their adoption.

00:51:52.270 --> 00:51:54.720
He confounds the first
American political party,

00:51:54.720 --> 00:51:56.540
then called the Republican Party.

00:51:56.540 --> 00:51:58.790
Now, it's still with us,
called the Democratic Party,

00:51:58.790 --> 00:52:01.090
and it's changed a bit.

00:52:01.090 --> 00:52:03.850 position:56%
But it was a remarkable achievement.

00:52:03.850 --> 00:52:07.650 position:56%
He was secretary of state during the
Louisiana Purchase, doubled the size

00:52:07.650 --> 00:52:10.060
of the nation, transformed
the nation.

00:52:10.060 --> 00:52:11.830
He was our first wartime president.

00:52:11.830 --> 00:52:14.900
He led us into the war of 1812.

00:52:14.900 --> 00:52:18.960
And I would maintain, and you
can think about this afterwards,

00:52:18.960 --> 00:52:21.890
that he was our only
two-term president

00:52:21.890 --> 00:52:25.160
who had a better second
term than his first term.

00:52:25.160 --> 00:52:27.590
If you think about the
presidents in our lifetime,

00:52:27.590 --> 00:52:30.690
the second term can be
tricky, Iran-Contra,

00:52:30.690 --> 00:52:35.520
Monica Lewinsky, housing crisis.

00:52:35.520 --> 00:52:39.680
Yet, Madison leaves office really
with an incredible swelling

00:52:39.680 --> 00:52:43.250
of support and prosperity
around the nation.

00:52:43.250 --> 00:52:46.660
So, that's his amazing
list of achievements.

00:52:46.660 --> 00:52:50.220
The second fact though is
that he is so often unnoticed.

00:52:50.220 --> 00:52:52.360
I found myself telling
my editor that he's sort

00:52:52.360 --> 00:52:54.390
of the zelig of the founding.

00:52:54.390 --> 00:52:58.600
He's always in the picture, but
nobody is paying attention to him.

00:52:58.600 --> 00:53:01.870
And it's an interesting
question, why was that?

00:53:01.870 --> 00:53:03.770
There is a flip answer.

00:53:03.770 --> 00:53:06.280
He was short, he was skinny,

00:53:06.280 --> 00:53:10.430
he had a small voice,
he was losing his hair.

00:53:10.430 --> 00:53:14.280
And in rooms filled with
noisy people like John Adams

00:53:14.280 --> 00:53:18.760 position:56%
and Alexander Hamilton or with large
charismatic figures like Washington

00:53:18.760 --> 00:53:22.810
and Thomas Jefferson,
Madison was easy to miss.

00:53:22.810 --> 00:53:27.870
I think that echoes through the
historical memory, and it is true.

00:53:27.870 --> 00:53:31.190
But there's another answer that I
think is a lot more interesting,

00:53:31.190 --> 00:53:34.940
which is that he really was
different from most great leaders.

00:53:34.940 --> 00:53:36.440
Most great leaders, and you--

00:53:36.440 --> 00:53:40.190
if your mind wanders to current
presidential candidates that--

00:53:40.190 --> 00:53:46.570
I can't prevent that, they often
have strong streaks of narcissism.

00:53:46.570 --> 00:53:48.330
They need to be at the
front of the parade,

00:53:48.330 --> 00:53:51.200
preferably on a white
horse with a band playing.

00:53:51.200 --> 00:53:54.190
They crave recognition and acclaim.

00:53:54.190 --> 00:53:55.840
Madison had none of that.

00:53:55.840 --> 00:53:59.870 position:56%
There's a wonderful moment when he's
at his inaugural ball as president

00:53:59.870 --> 00:54:04.070
in 1809, it's the first
inaugural ball ever,

00:54:04.070 --> 00:54:06.480
and an on old friend
comes up embraces him

00:54:06.480 --> 00:54:08.480
and says, "Isn't this wonderful."

00:54:08.480 --> 00:54:11.920
And Madison says, "Well, I'd
really rather be home in bed,"

00:54:11.920 --> 00:54:14.010
which was really Madison.

00:54:14.010 --> 00:54:16.970
He cared about results,
not applause,

00:54:16.970 --> 00:54:20.350 position:56%
about making the American experiment
and self-government a success

00:54:20.350 --> 00:54:23.490
in realizing the promise
of the revolution.

00:54:23.490 --> 00:54:27.380
I was struck by a description
by a long-term colleague

00:54:27.380 --> 00:54:30.610
that under all circumstances, he
was ever mindful of what was due

00:54:30.610 --> 00:54:35.450
from him to others and cautious not
to wound the feelings of anyone.

00:54:35.450 --> 00:54:38.190
I think many of our leaders
are very mindful of what is due

00:54:38.190 --> 00:54:42.780 position:56%
from to them, much less the reverse.

00:54:42.780 --> 00:54:47.970
I became persuaded also that
many of his great achievements,

00:54:47.970 --> 00:54:51.610
really most of them, were the
result of great partnerships.

00:54:51.610 --> 00:54:55.110
And it was almost as though he
had taken a modern personality

00:54:55.110 --> 00:54:58.260 position:56%
assessment, one of these things that
determines whether you're an ISPJ

00:54:58.260 --> 00:55:03.430
or an introvert or an extrovert,
and had concluded that he was

00:55:03.430 --> 00:55:08.000
in fact short, he was
skinny, he has a small voice

00:55:08.000 --> 00:55:10.810
and he had zero personal magnetism.

00:55:10.810 --> 00:55:17.780 position:56%
All true. But an honest self
assessment would also have concluded

00:55:17.780 --> 00:55:20.470
that he was smarter than
almost everybody he met.

00:55:20.470 --> 00:55:22.650
He had a rear capacity
for hard work.

00:55:22.650 --> 00:55:24.830
He had good political
judgment and foresight.

00:55:24.830 --> 00:55:29.850
And he had a gift and that's the
gift in the title of my book.

00:55:29.850 --> 00:55:34.670
A gift for working with others
for checking his ego at the door

00:55:34.670 --> 00:55:37.260
and making something happen.

00:55:37.260 --> 00:55:42.290
That gave me the lens to
look at his career as a man

00:55:42.290 --> 00:55:45.360
who understood the
power of partnership.

00:55:45.360 --> 00:55:48.380
I studied particularly
five partnerships

00:55:48.380 --> 00:55:51.600
because this is a somewhat
condensed program I'm going

00:55:51.600 --> 00:55:53.270
to speed through them.

00:55:53.270 --> 00:55:58.120
The fifth one I may linger on
for a minute because it was,

00:55:58.120 --> 00:56:00.100
for me, the most interesting.

00:56:00.100 --> 00:56:05.840
The first of course was Hamilton
but this was before he could rap.

00:56:05.840 --> 00:56:08.660
But he was such a contrast
in character, flashy,

00:56:08.660 --> 00:56:12.030
charismatic personality, an
orphan from the West Indies,

00:56:12.030 --> 00:56:15.470
comes with nothing,
incredible talent.

00:56:15.470 --> 00:56:19.020
He was good at everything,
he tried soldier,

00:56:19.020 --> 00:56:21.900
lawyer, statesman, financier.

00:56:21.900 --> 00:56:28.380
And he meets this quiet fellow from
Virginia who's a fortunate son.

00:56:28.380 --> 00:56:33.130
His father owns 5,000 acres
of land and 100 slaves.

00:56:33.130 --> 00:56:37.080
And they connect, this is in
the early 1780's and a Congress

00:56:37.080 --> 00:56:40.820
that was not filled with
distinguished people.

00:56:40.820 --> 00:56:43.610
And they recognized in each
other, I think, two things.

00:56:43.610 --> 00:56:47.990
One was that they both were
smarter than everybody else.

00:56:47.990 --> 00:56:50.120
And that they both were committed

00:56:50.120 --> 00:56:53.640
to making the United
States a great place

00:56:53.640 --> 00:56:57.070
and a great nation in the world.

00:56:57.070 --> 00:56:59.790
They collaborated on the calling

00:56:59.790 --> 00:57:04.050
of the convention arguably the
most important step that was taken

00:57:04.050 --> 00:57:05.390
in creating this new government.

00:57:05.390 --> 00:57:09.200
And then, at the convention,
Madison had an up

00:57:09.200 --> 00:57:11.310
and down convention as
Marry has described.

00:57:11.310 --> 00:57:14.850
Hamilton had a catastrophic
convention.

00:57:14.850 --> 00:57:19.210
He actually gave a speech
that lasted for five hours.

00:57:19.210 --> 00:57:21.910
That alone is enough
to cause trouble.

00:57:21.910 --> 00:57:26.080
But he then, in his speech, argued
in favor of a president for life

00:57:26.080 --> 00:57:28.600
and a Senate that would
serve for life.

00:57:28.600 --> 00:57:31.310
But he came back at the
end of the convention

00:57:31.310 --> 00:57:35.320
and announced he would support the
constitution even though no man's

00:57:35.320 --> 00:57:38.960
opinions are more different
from this than mine.

00:57:38.960 --> 00:57:42.630
And he's the one who came up with
the idea for the federalist papers

00:57:42.630 --> 00:57:47.450
as an advocacy piece to get people
to support the constitution.

00:57:47.450 --> 00:57:51.650 position:56%
Because when it was published,
there was much more opposition than,

00:57:51.650 --> 00:57:54.370
I think, they had anticipated.

00:57:54.370 --> 00:57:56.330
He tried to recruit
people to help them

00:57:56.330 --> 00:57:58.880
with the writing, three
didn't work out.

00:57:58.880 --> 00:58:01.740
He ended up finding-- his
fourth choice was James Madison

00:58:01.740 --> 00:58:03.080
and a brilliant choice it was.

00:58:03.080 --> 00:58:07.710
They ended up producing 190,000
words of extraordinary insight.

00:58:07.710 --> 00:58:09.780
Then, they put down
their pens and went off

00:58:09.780 --> 00:58:13.100
and led the ratification fights
in their state conventions.

00:58:13.100 --> 00:58:16.440
Now, the second alliance

00:58:16.440 --> 00:58:19.180
or partnership was
with George Washington.

00:58:19.180 --> 00:58:22.590
He was not a pear, nobody
was a pear of Washington,

00:58:22.590 --> 00:58:26.560
I'll quote the great Miranda again.

00:58:26.560 --> 00:58:30.240
There's a moment in the show
when George the third learns

00:58:30.240 --> 00:58:31.690
that Washington is resigning,

00:58:31.690 --> 00:58:34.160
which he can't believe anybody
would actually give up power.

00:58:34.160 --> 00:58:37.150
He says, "Can you do that?"

00:58:37.150 --> 00:58:41.450
And he hears that John Adams
is going to be his successor

00:58:41.450 --> 00:58:46.600
and he says, "Compared to
Washington, they all seem small."

00:58:46.600 --> 00:58:54.520
And that was the way our society
had to develop our nation.

00:58:54.520 --> 00:58:58.360
Madison figured out very fast that
if he wanted to have an impact

00:58:58.360 --> 00:59:01.850
on the new nation,
he-- standing close

00:59:01.850 --> 00:59:03.950
to Washington was a great idea.

00:59:03.950 --> 00:59:07.290
Washington is famously referred
to as the indispensable man

00:59:07.290 --> 00:59:09.380
and Madison made himself
the indispensable man

00:59:09.380 --> 00:59:11.590
to the indispensable man.

00:59:11.590 --> 00:59:14.440
He got legislation
that Washington wanted.

00:59:14.440 --> 00:59:17.020
He wrote speeches that
Washington needed.

00:59:17.020 --> 00:59:20.410
He famously wrote the inaugural
address that Washington delivers

00:59:20.410 --> 00:59:22.830
at the beginning of the government.

00:59:22.830 --> 00:59:27.120 position:56%
And there's a wonderful moment then
when Congress receives this address.

00:59:27.120 --> 00:59:30.350
It's short, it's very measured,

00:59:30.350 --> 00:59:32.330
only asks for one thing,
the Bill of Rights.

00:59:32.330 --> 00:59:34.510
And they think, well, we're
setting presidents here,

00:59:34.510 --> 00:59:36.170
we ought to acknowledge the speech.

00:59:36.170 --> 00:59:39.830
So, they need to come up with
something to say in response.

00:59:39.830 --> 00:59:43.110
So, they asked James
Madison to write it.

00:59:43.110 --> 00:59:45.730
And then, Washington
gets their response

00:59:45.730 --> 00:59:49.310
and he's a courtly Virginian and
he doesn't want to give offense

00:59:49.310 --> 00:59:51.150
so he needs to say
something in replay.

00:59:51.150 --> 00:59:54.080
So, asks Madison to write that.

00:59:54.080 --> 00:59:57.480
So, the early year of the
government is, in many ways,

00:59:57.480 --> 00:59:59.520
James Madison talking to himself.

00:59:59.520 --> 01:00:03.980
The third partnership
is with Thomas Jefferson

01:00:03.980 --> 01:00:08.440
and that's the one we mostly
think of with Madison.

01:00:08.440 --> 01:00:09.740
They were soul mates.

01:00:09.740 --> 01:00:12.090
They grow up 30 miles apart.

01:00:12.090 --> 01:00:14.720
They-- Jefferson was
eight years older

01:00:14.720 --> 01:00:17.370
but they had so much in common.

01:00:17.370 --> 01:00:21.230
They were both fortunate
sons with rich fathers.

01:00:21.230 --> 01:00:27.170
And I focused on a part of
their relationship which lasted

01:00:27.170 --> 01:00:31.340
for 40 years and covered
every subject.

01:00:31.340 --> 01:00:35.290
What I focused on was
the achievement, I think,

01:00:35.290 --> 01:00:38.740
they would probably
be least proud of,

01:00:38.740 --> 01:00:41.860
which is creating America's
first political party.

01:00:41.860 --> 01:00:47.330
This was an era when it was stylish
and necessary for a public figure

01:00:47.330 --> 01:00:49.780
to insist that he really
didn't believe in parties,

01:00:49.780 --> 01:00:52.170
that they were the elements--

01:00:52.170 --> 01:00:55.190
that they were the
instruments of self interest.

01:00:55.190 --> 01:01:02.190
Small minded people were engaged
in factionalism not great leaders.

01:01:02.190 --> 01:01:05.830
But Jefferson and Madison
found themselves

01:01:05.830 --> 01:01:08.960
with a big problem
in the early 1790's.

01:01:08.960 --> 01:01:12.770
Hamilton and his financial
program were being the adopted.

01:01:12.770 --> 01:01:16.360
Washington supported them
and did not support Madison

01:01:16.360 --> 01:01:21.600
and Jefferson's view that those
financial programs were dangerous

01:01:21.600 --> 01:01:24.710
that they would create a
much more powerful government

01:01:24.710 --> 01:01:28.360
than they had intended
or that we should have.

01:01:28.360 --> 01:01:32.390
And they needed to oppose it but
they couldn't oppose Washington.

01:01:32.390 --> 01:01:38.290
So they began developing what was
originally the republican interest

01:01:38.290 --> 01:01:39.820
in Congress.

01:01:39.820 --> 01:01:42.360
Around Madison, he--
like minded Congressman

01:01:42.360 --> 01:01:45.510
and began to gather around him.

01:01:45.510 --> 01:01:48.450
They then reached out to
political leaders in the states

01:01:48.450 --> 01:01:51.200
and ultimately recruited
newspaper editors

01:01:51.200 --> 01:01:54.990
and they formed the Republican
Party by the election of 1796.

01:01:54.990 --> 01:01:56.490
They have an actual party.

01:01:56.490 --> 01:02:01.190
In then, in 1800, Jefferson
wins the election.

01:02:01.190 --> 01:02:03.580
It's often said that the
true test of a democracy

01:02:03.580 --> 01:02:06.420
or a republic is whether you can
have a peaceful transfer of power

01:02:06.420 --> 01:02:08.280
between contending parties.

01:02:08.280 --> 01:02:12.660
We passed that test in 1800
with that political party.

01:02:12.660 --> 01:02:18.240
An externally powerful force
for much of our life as a nation

01:02:18.240 --> 01:02:21.570
but certainly, the first 60 years
from 1800 until the Civil War,

01:02:21.570 --> 01:02:24.270
it was the dominant
political party in a way

01:02:24.270 --> 01:02:27.190
that we really haven't seen since.

01:02:27.190 --> 01:02:32.480
The fourth partnership
was with James Monroe.

01:02:32.480 --> 01:02:36.020
Monroe was not somebody
you would ask to write any

01:02:36.020 --> 01:02:37.320
of the federalist papers.

01:02:37.320 --> 01:02:38.620
He was a military figure.

01:02:38.620 --> 01:02:40.920
I was a little distressed
to find that many

01:02:40.920 --> 01:02:43.570
of his contemporaries
would say of Monroe, "Well,

01:02:43.570 --> 01:02:47.940
he's a nice fellow but
he's a little dim."

01:02:47.940 --> 01:02:49.350
And it seemed that Madison

01:02:49.350 --> 01:02:54.280
and he had a much more
relaxed relationship with--

01:02:54.280 --> 01:02:57.370
the correspondence between
Madison and Jefferson is wonderful,

01:02:57.370 --> 01:02:59.760
it's rich, they talk
about everything.

01:02:59.760 --> 01:03:02.590
You know, that design
of hinges and philosophy

01:03:02.590 --> 01:03:07.010
and science and some politics.

01:03:07.010 --> 01:03:14.440
With Monroe, the subject is
politics and it just feels he--

01:03:14.440 --> 01:03:18.450
Madison doesn't have to work as
hard when he's dealing with Monroe.

01:03:18.450 --> 01:03:22.730
An interesting feature
of their relationship was

01:03:22.730 --> 01:03:27.570
that they were opponents,
direct opponents twice.

01:03:27.570 --> 01:03:32.850
First, in a campaign for
the Congress in 1789,

01:03:32.850 --> 01:03:36.640
when the first Congress was
elected, Madison was identified

01:03:36.640 --> 01:03:39.170
with the ratification forces.

01:03:39.170 --> 01:03:42.820
And the people who opposed
that, principally Patrick Henry

01:03:42.820 --> 01:03:45.060
in Virginia wanted to be Madison.

01:03:45.060 --> 01:03:46.730
It was going to be the post--

01:03:46.730 --> 01:03:50.910
he would be the poster child
of the bad constitution.

01:03:50.910 --> 01:03:55.420
So they recruited this handsome
strapping military veteran,

01:03:55.420 --> 01:03:57.490
James Monroe to run against him.

01:03:57.490 --> 01:04:00.990
And in an era when people stood
for election rather than run

01:04:00.990 --> 01:04:03.060
for election, and Madison
hated to campaign,

01:04:03.060 --> 01:04:05.060
he really had to campaign
against Monroe.

01:04:05.060 --> 01:04:11.030
They went around the district
doing campaign events at churches.

01:04:11.030 --> 01:04:16.340
And he did ultimately win
that contest pretty handily.

01:04:16.340 --> 01:04:19.330
But then, 20 years
later they fall out.

01:04:19.330 --> 01:04:23.460
And I skipped one thing, even
though they opposed each other,

01:04:23.460 --> 01:04:25.640
they pick up their friendship
immediately thereafter

01:04:25.640 --> 01:04:27.570
without any real trouble.

01:04:27.570 --> 01:04:30.970
Twenty years later it
doesn't work that way.

01:04:30.970 --> 01:04:33.210
Monroe is in England.

01:04:33.210 --> 01:04:35.500
He's asked to negotiate a
treaty with the British.

01:04:35.500 --> 01:04:39.100
It's a very tough assignment.

01:04:39.100 --> 01:04:41.810
The British and the French are
fighting the Napoleonic Wars,

01:04:41.810 --> 01:04:44.200
it's a duel to the death.

01:04:44.200 --> 01:04:46.730
They're both praying on our
shipping and on our sailors

01:04:46.730 --> 01:04:51.590
and they could care less about
America, we're military weak.

01:04:51.590 --> 01:04:57.580
And so, to try to get some
piece, Jefferson asked Monroe

01:04:57.580 --> 01:05:00.360
to negotiate this treaty.

01:05:00.360 --> 01:05:03.630
Monroe spent three years on it,
sends back a terrible treaty.

01:05:03.630 --> 01:05:05.580
He got nothing.

01:05:05.580 --> 01:05:08.610
And Madison and Jefferson
on the first day agreed

01:05:08.610 --> 01:05:12.290 position:56%
that they would simply put it in the
files and never speak of it again.

01:05:12.290 --> 01:05:18.610
Monroe was mortified and he-- then,
when he comes back to this country

01:05:18.610 --> 01:05:23.470 position:56%
in 1908, he allows his name to be
entered as in an opponent of Madison

01:05:23.470 --> 01:05:25.950
in the presidential election.

01:05:25.950 --> 01:05:32.190
And I could find no trace of
Madison taking any step to campaign

01:05:32.190 --> 01:05:35.030 position:56%
for the office of president in 1808.

01:05:35.030 --> 01:05:36.340
He must have done something.

01:05:36.340 --> 01:05:38.210
I mean, he had to talk
to some people.

01:05:38.210 --> 01:05:40.450
It just had to happen.

01:05:40.450 --> 01:05:44.230
But with Monroe, you can find
some evidence that he was working

01:05:44.230 --> 01:05:45.800
with a few people on his campaign.

01:05:45.800 --> 01:05:48.550
His campaign was really
not a serious matter.

01:05:48.550 --> 01:05:50.970
He only got three electoral votes.

01:05:50.970 --> 01:05:54.990
But he was bitter and it was a
measure of how bitter he was.

01:05:54.990 --> 01:06:00.480
And for two years, these close
friends for decades did not speak

01:06:00.480 --> 01:06:02.870
and did not have any connection.

01:06:02.870 --> 01:06:05.270
They did not correspond.

01:06:05.270 --> 01:06:09.380
Ultimately, Madison is-- knows
he's going to end up with a war

01:06:09.380 --> 01:06:12.340
with Britain, he needs a
strong secretary of state.

01:06:12.340 --> 01:06:15.800
He cannot abide the one he has
a fellow named Robert Smith

01:06:15.800 --> 01:06:19.750
from Maryland who was an
unfortunate public official.

01:06:19.750 --> 01:06:22.340
And it was hard to
get fired by Madison.

01:06:22.340 --> 01:06:28.490 position:56%
But Smith managed too and Madison
at that point reaches out to Monroe.

01:06:28.490 --> 01:06:32.770
Recruits him back in to
the family, basically.

01:06:32.770 --> 01:06:36.780
Appoints him secretary of state
and Monroe was a key member

01:06:36.780 --> 01:06:38.560
of his administration,
served as secretary

01:06:38.560 --> 01:06:39.860
of state, secretary of war.

01:06:39.860 --> 01:06:43.260 position:56%
And for two periods, he served
simultaneously as secretary of state

01:06:43.260 --> 01:06:47.550
and secretary of war,
which is unparalleled.

01:06:47.550 --> 01:06:50.570
No on else has ever done that.

01:06:50.570 --> 01:06:54.540
Now, the final partnership of
course is with his wife Dolley.

01:06:54.540 --> 01:06:58.530
You know, I'd like to spend
a minute or two more with her

01:06:58.530 --> 01:07:01.760
because she's so much fun.

01:07:01.760 --> 01:07:05.330
She was originally Dolley Payne.

01:07:05.330 --> 01:07:09.610
She came from the Virginia
plantation world

01:07:09.610 --> 01:07:13.940
but with one big difference
from Madison's background,

01:07:13.940 --> 01:07:18.010
her family was Quaker and
when she was a young teenager,

01:07:18.010 --> 01:07:22.350
the Quaker meeting in Virginia
decreed that all good members

01:07:22.350 --> 01:07:25.510
of the Quaker meeting
would not own slaves.

01:07:25.510 --> 01:07:30.860
So, Mr. Payne freed his slaves and
moved his family to Philadelphia

01:07:30.860 --> 01:07:34.680
where he promptly became
a cropper in business.

01:07:34.680 --> 01:07:38.670 position:56%
His wife was forced to convert their
house into a boarding house in order

01:07:38.670 --> 01:07:40.940
to keep food on the table.

01:07:40.940 --> 01:07:47.930
But Dolley flourished,
she was tall for her time.

01:07:47.930 --> 01:07:51.810
She had an hour glass figure, a
mischievous smile, black hair,

01:07:51.810 --> 01:07:55.740
creamy complexion, bright blue
eyes, men liked her a lot.

01:07:55.740 --> 01:07:59.270
And I always like to point out
that Madison surely was short

01:07:59.270 --> 01:08:01.680
and he was loosing his
hair and he was skinny.

01:08:01.680 --> 01:08:06.120
But of all the frank founders,
he had the hottest wife.

01:08:07.300 --> 01:08:12.510
Dolley had a first husband,
he and one of their sons died

01:08:12.510 --> 01:08:14.790
in the yellow fever
epidemic of 1793,

01:08:14.790 --> 01:08:17.470
leaving her as a single mother.

01:08:17.470 --> 01:08:22.690
Madison somehow became aware of her
and fascinated by her, she was--

01:08:22.690 --> 01:08:24.750
she had many suitors not just he.

01:08:24.750 --> 01:08:29.070
And you can see her playful
nature and sophistication

01:08:29.070 --> 01:08:32.290
in the letter she writes the
day that Senator Aaron Burr is

01:08:32.290 --> 01:08:37.560
to bring Madison over to introduce
him, Burr was actually a lodger

01:08:37.560 --> 01:08:40.970
in Mrs. Payne's boardinghouse.

01:08:40.970 --> 01:08:45.450
And Dolley writes that she's going
to meet the great little Madison.

01:08:45.450 --> 01:08:48.750
And it's perfect because he was
little but he also was great.

01:08:48.750 --> 01:08:50.050
He was rich.

01:08:50.050 --> 01:08:51.350
He was intelligent.

01:08:51.350 --> 01:08:53.360
He was kind and he was
a political power house.

01:08:53.360 --> 01:08:57.260
You could do a lot worse than James
Madison and she understood it.

01:08:57.260 --> 01:09:02.660
Writing about Dolley gave me
a chance to see some sides

01:09:02.660 --> 01:09:05.130
of Madison you don't often see.

01:09:05.130 --> 01:09:07.980
Let me just mention a couple.

01:09:07.980 --> 01:09:09.670
In their first term
in the White House,

01:09:09.670 --> 01:09:14.290 position:56%
Dolley's sister Lucy was widowed and
so she moved into the White House

01:09:14.290 --> 01:09:18.810
with her three children and
lived there for three years.

01:09:18.810 --> 01:09:22.060
And Madison really enjoyed Lucy
but apparently something he liked

01:09:22.060 --> 01:09:26.980
to do was to kiss Dolley in front
of Lucy and turn to Lucy and say,

01:09:26.980 --> 01:09:29.680
"Does that make your mouth water?"

01:09:29.680 --> 01:09:32.230 position:56%
It's a little creepy, I'll admit it.

01:09:32.230 --> 01:09:40.070
But, you've never thought about
James Madison that way before.

01:09:40.070 --> 01:09:41.850 position:56%
They never had children of their own

01:09:41.850 --> 01:09:44.580
but they were not this
semi-sad childless couple

01:09:44.580 --> 01:09:45.880
that is sometimes imagined.

01:09:45.880 --> 01:09:49.370
They had more than 50 nieces and
nephews who often were with them,

01:09:49.370 --> 01:09:53.060
which spend weeks and
months living with them.

01:09:53.060 --> 01:09:58.970 position:56%
James, although as very dull fellow
in a large setting, was quite lively

01:09:58.970 --> 01:10:02.960
and entertaining in smaller groups
known to tell great anecdotes.

01:10:02.960 --> 01:10:09.580
Dolley was always fun and it
was always fun with a purpose.

01:10:09.580 --> 01:10:13.790
They were setting a social
tone for the whole nation.

01:10:13.790 --> 01:10:18.700
One of my favorite stories
involves in retirement,

01:10:18.700 --> 01:10:23.560
Dolley had grown wider with
the years, James had not.

01:10:23.560 --> 01:10:27.530 position:56%
And she would load him up on her
back and carry him around the house.

01:10:27.530 --> 01:10:32.050
And they ran races on front
portico of Montpellier.

01:10:32.050 --> 01:10:34.110
They were fun.

01:10:34.110 --> 01:10:39.030
But Dolley was in truth of
political partner as well,

01:10:39.030 --> 01:10:43.520 position:56%
she had to be vivacious and
charming and the center of attention

01:10:43.520 --> 01:10:45.900
because James couldn't do it.

01:10:45.900 --> 01:10:49.310
And during his presidency,
they would have a couple

01:10:49.310 --> 01:10:52.630
of social events a week and she
would started wearing white turbans

01:10:52.630 --> 01:10:58.020
of velvet or silk and she would
put flowers in the top or feathers

01:10:58.020 --> 01:11:00.090
or even a piece of fruit.

01:11:00.090 --> 01:11:03.100
And James would come and
great everybody very soberly

01:11:03.100 --> 01:11:05.620
and work the whole room and
then go off into a corner

01:11:05.620 --> 01:11:09.040
with some gentlemen
and talk business.

01:11:09.040 --> 01:11:10.500
Dolley would be in the
middle of the room,

01:11:10.500 --> 01:11:12.160
everybody would know who she was.

01:11:12.160 --> 01:11:15.740
Everyone would be listening with
one ear to what she was saying.

01:11:15.740 --> 01:11:20.810
And she made his career
far more effective.

01:11:20.810 --> 01:11:28.420
Indeed, the man who lost
Madison in 1808 wrote

01:11:28.420 --> 01:11:32.000
that he had lost to
Mr and Mrs. Madison.

01:11:32.000 --> 01:11:35.610
I might have had a better chance
had I faced Mr. Madison alone.

01:11:35.610 --> 01:11:39.770
And Dolley, of course,
is often best remembered

01:11:39.770 --> 01:11:43.580
for saving the Gilbert Stuart
portrait when the British came

01:11:43.580 --> 01:11:47.010
to burn the public
buildings of Washington.

01:11:47.010 --> 01:11:50.910
I think, we tend not to appreciate
the importance of that at the time.

01:11:50.910 --> 01:11:53.600
America had no kings,
we had no history,

01:11:53.600 --> 01:11:55.990
the nation was not
even 30 years old.

01:11:55.990 --> 01:11:57.800
What we had was George Washington

01:11:57.800 --> 01:12:01.190
and that Stuart portrait
had been made into prints

01:12:01.190 --> 01:12:04.680
and those prints hung
in many American homes.

01:12:04.680 --> 01:12:08.790 position:56%
And had we lost the Stuart portrait,
it would have been, in fact,

01:12:08.790 --> 01:12:11.540
a great blow to American morale,

01:12:11.540 --> 01:12:16.220
at a time when having foreign
troops burn our public buildings

01:12:16.220 --> 01:12:22.030 position:56%
and our national capital was already
a tremendous blow to our morale.

01:12:22.030 --> 01:12:25.040 position:56%
Let me just mention two last things.

01:12:26.760 --> 01:12:29.910 position:56%
Mary talked about this and I'm glad.

01:12:29.910 --> 01:12:34.370
It's easy for us to get
lost in sort of wonder

01:12:34.370 --> 01:12:36.950
of his times and his achievements.

01:12:36.950 --> 01:12:39.200
But I think it is important
for us never to forget

01:12:39.200 --> 01:12:44.690
that he was a slave
holder for 85 years.

01:12:44.690 --> 01:12:47.510
The question tortured him.

01:12:47.510 --> 01:12:50.880
He understood completely the
hypocrisy between what he said

01:12:50.880 --> 01:12:54.480
in terms of being committed to
human liberty and the way he lived.

01:12:54.480 --> 01:12:58.780
As a young man, he bought land
up in Mohawk Valley of New York

01:12:58.780 --> 01:13:00.080
and wrote a friend that he hope

01:13:00.080 --> 01:13:05.120
to live there never relying
on the labor of others.

01:13:05.120 --> 01:13:06.420
He never did it.

01:13:06.420 --> 01:13:09.610
I think it was awfully comfortable
having those hundreds slaves

01:13:09.610 --> 01:13:13.380
and Virginia gave him an
amazing political platform.

01:13:13.380 --> 01:13:17.580
Jefferson was a neighbor,
Washington was a fellow countryman.

01:13:17.580 --> 01:13:20.500
It was the biggest
state in the union.

01:13:20.500 --> 01:13:23.680
But then, in his retirement
years, again,

01:13:23.680 --> 01:13:25.890
with sort of a nascent
abolition movement,

01:13:25.890 --> 01:13:29.000
he became tortured
by this issue more.

01:13:29.000 --> 01:13:33.380
He wrote memos to himself about,
which was something he did,

01:13:33.380 --> 01:13:38.600
about how he might sell off all the
lands out west and use the money

01:13:38.600 --> 01:13:42.500
to buy slaves out of bondage
and ship them somewhere else.

01:13:42.500 --> 01:13:46.070
They were all a pipe
dream but it was a measure

01:13:46.070 --> 01:13:51.830
of what he really did understand
was unfinished business in his life

01:13:51.830 --> 01:13:56.670
and a permanent mark on his legacy.

01:13:56.670 --> 01:14:00.700
And I have talked a good bit
about his partnerships of course,

01:14:00.700 --> 01:14:06.390
but I'd like to close by
focusing again on Madison himself.

01:14:06.390 --> 01:14:11.700
He is often portrayed as
this disembodied intellect.

01:14:11.700 --> 01:14:14.470
But I do think his greatest
qualities were his genuineness

01:14:14.470 --> 01:14:17.110
and integrity and modesty
and open-heartedness.

01:14:17.110 --> 01:14:21.420
That's what all these
different partners found in him.

01:14:21.420 --> 01:14:23.460
And I thought that
those qualities shown

01:14:23.460 --> 01:14:26.950
through in the way he received
the news of the Treaty of Ghent

01:14:26.950 --> 01:14:29.540
that ended the War of 1812.

01:14:29.540 --> 01:14:33.320
It's in February of 1815, he's
living in the Octagon House

01:14:33.320 --> 01:14:37.330
over on 17th street because of
course, the White House was burned.

01:14:37.330 --> 01:14:42.240
And a rumor arrives that a treaty
has been signed with Britain.

01:14:42.240 --> 01:14:45.010
A Pennsylvania senator
rushes to the Octagon House

01:14:45.010 --> 01:14:47.080
to ask the president if it's true.

01:14:47.080 --> 01:14:52.940
Let me just read a couple
of sentence from the book.

01:14:52.940 --> 01:14:56.490
"The senator found the house dark,
the president sitting solitary

01:14:56.490 --> 01:14:59.420
in his parlor, in perfect
tranquility,

01:14:59.420 --> 01:15:01.850
not even a servant in waiting.

01:15:01.850 --> 01:15:04.740
The senator asked if
the rumor was true.

01:15:04.740 --> 01:15:06.300
Madison bade him sit down.

01:15:06.300 --> 01:15:10.390
"I will tell you all I know,"
he said, then confirmed

01:15:10.390 --> 01:15:14.770 position:56%
that he thought there was peace,
but he had no official confirmation.

01:15:14.770 --> 01:15:16.570
The senator recalled
with some wonder,

01:15:16.570 --> 01:15:21.540
what he called the president's self
command, and greatness of mind.

01:15:21.540 --> 01:15:24.690
The world of 1812 had truly
been Mr. Madison's war

01:15:24.690 --> 01:15:26.940
as his opponents called it.

01:15:26.940 --> 01:15:29.450
It was about principles not gain.

01:15:29.450 --> 01:15:33.420
It was fought with a quiet
tenacity often ineptly,

01:15:33.420 --> 01:15:38.050
and with endless tolerance
of those who opposed it.

01:15:38.050 --> 01:15:39.760
A friend of Madison's
wrote years later,

01:15:39.760 --> 01:15:42.780
that the war had been
conducted in perfect keeping

01:15:42.780 --> 01:15:45.420 position:56%
with the character of the president.

01:15:45.420 --> 01:15:49.670
And when peace came, Madison
welcomed it a darkened house,

01:15:49.670 --> 01:15:51.910
sitting alone with his thoughts."

01:15:51.910 --> 01:15:53.710
Thank you.

01:15:53.710 --> 01:16:00.950
[ Applause ]

01:16:00.950 --> 01:16:02.250
