01:17:40.370 --> 01:17:43.420
&gt;&gt; Let me see.

01:17:44.710 --> 01:17:52.650
Dr. Bilder mentioned that in the
notes, Madison had in his notes one

01:17:52.650 --> 01:17:58.020
of the significant pages on which
you-- he wrote a lot of footnotes

01:17:58.020 --> 01:18:03.870
and a lot of-- all around
the page was an apology

01:18:03.870 --> 01:18:07.550
for his position regarding
an autocratic president

01:18:07.550 --> 01:18:11.750
who would serve for
an indefinite term.

01:18:11.750 --> 01:18:16.070
And then, David Stewart mentioned
that same thing about Hamilton

01:18:16.070 --> 01:18:19.220
that in his five-hour
speech proposed this

01:18:19.220 --> 01:18:21.210
and it was not well received.

01:18:21.210 --> 01:18:24.770
I'm wondering if you could--
I'm curious to understand why--

01:18:24.770 --> 01:18:31.170
what was the thinking behind their
belief that this was a good form

01:18:31.170 --> 01:18:34.650
of a good aspect of
the government to have,

01:18:34.650 --> 01:18:37.770
a president who would serve
without a definite term?

01:18:37.770 --> 01:18:40.590
&gt;&gt; Mary Sarah Bilder:
Well, I'll start and then--

01:18:40.590 --> 01:18:44.410
and David who wrote but also
in his first book can chip in.

01:18:44.410 --> 01:18:51.000
There-- Hamilton gives this great
speech, this long speech in June

01:18:51.000 --> 01:18:53.360
and people have different
interpretations about it.

01:18:53.360 --> 01:18:56.490
Did he really mean it
or did he not mean it.

01:18:56.490 --> 01:19:03.560
I believe it was a strategy,
at that time, the national plan

01:19:03.560 --> 01:19:07.530
that had been proposed by the
Virginians was under attack

01:19:07.530 --> 01:19:12.930
by the small states who wanted
a very weak-- a weak plan.

01:19:12.930 --> 01:19:18.210
And I think my own view on this
is that Hamilton basically agreed

01:19:18.210 --> 01:19:25.260
to walk in and give a speech
that suggested that the--

01:19:25.260 --> 01:19:26.660
that there could be
a far worse plan.

01:19:26.660 --> 01:19:29.730
And Hamilton's plan was
actually never adopted.

01:19:29.730 --> 01:19:33.150
He never introduced it formally,
he just spoke and if you look

01:19:33.150 --> 01:19:35.710
at the plan that was
recorded by Madison,

01:19:35.710 --> 01:19:38.090
Hamilton went out of his
way to make everything

01:19:38.090 --> 01:19:41.020
like as extreme as possible.

01:19:41.020 --> 01:19:42.450
So, I think in a funny way,

01:19:42.450 --> 01:19:44.550
I don't know if people
remember a very fine book

01:19:44.550 --> 01:19:47.160
by political scientist
Graham Allison,

01:19:47.160 --> 01:19:50.780
that argues that policy
makers inevitably move

01:19:50.780 --> 01:19:54.020
to the B position once presented
with an A and C. And so,

01:19:54.020 --> 01:19:58.500
I happen to believe that
Hamilton created a C position

01:19:58.500 --> 01:20:02.100
under which the national
plan became seen as moderate.

01:20:02.100 --> 01:20:05.940
I think that was plausible because
Hamilton was from that world

01:20:05.940 --> 01:20:08.540
and he did want strong power.

01:20:08.540 --> 01:20:11.050
So, I think that explains
Hamilton's position, I--

01:20:11.050 --> 01:20:15.520
you know, there was no
president in the western world

01:20:15.520 --> 01:20:18.870
so they were trying to figure out
what a president would look like

01:20:18.870 --> 01:20:24.270
and they were really wrestling with
this incredibly difficult notion

01:20:24.270 --> 01:20:27.990 position:56%
of how did you get the president
elected and then allow the president

01:20:27.990 --> 01:20:30.770
to be independent of control.

01:20:30.770 --> 01:20:34.020
And at that time, they assumed
the president would be elected

01:20:34.020 --> 01:20:36.610
by Congress and that the
senate would be elected

01:20:36.610 --> 01:20:38.120
by the state legislators.

01:20:38.120 --> 01:20:41.310
So, for Madison, the anxiety
is that the president is going

01:20:41.310 --> 01:20:44.490
to become a man totally
of the state legislatures.

01:20:44.490 --> 01:20:51.600
And so, at that moment he, I think,
votes strategically thinking,

01:20:51.600 --> 01:20:54.820
arguably maybe this would
be better but more likely

01:20:54.820 --> 01:20:57.580
that it would shock
people into trying

01:20:57.580 --> 01:21:01.130
to think how you make the
president more independent.

01:21:01.130 --> 01:21:04.770
And it's still a really
difficult question.

01:21:04.770 --> 01:21:07.370
So, in some ways, I think
they're both moments

01:21:07.370 --> 01:21:09.210
where there's strategic moments.

01:21:09.210 --> 01:21:13.640
But David's also written about
particularly the Hamilton part.

01:21:13.640 --> 01:21:14.940
&gt;&gt; David O. Stewart: Yeah.

01:21:14.940 --> 01:21:19.510
Hamilton may have been
interested in the strategic notion

01:21:19.510 --> 01:21:23.900
that it would terrify the
state's rights people.

01:21:23.900 --> 01:21:27.850
But I do think it was
what he believed in.

01:21:27.850 --> 01:21:30.270
I think he did believe
it was critical

01:21:30.270 --> 01:21:36.020
to have a powerful executive,
an independent executive

01:21:36.020 --> 01:21:39.110
and both Hamilton and Madison
worried about stability.

01:21:39.110 --> 01:21:44.850
It's a point on which
Madison often disagreed

01:21:44.850 --> 01:21:48.730
with Jefferson, one of the few.

01:21:48.730 --> 01:21:51.890
And Madison cared about stability.

01:21:51.890 --> 01:21:57.320
So, my reading of Hamilton's
moment in the convention

01:21:57.320 --> 01:22:01.390
and his later behavior
where he basically leaves

01:22:01.390 --> 01:22:04.160
because he's being denounced,
many other delegates talked

01:22:04.160 --> 01:22:08.750
about what a dopey
idea his speech was.

01:22:08.750 --> 01:22:12.000
And his fellow New York
delegates have also left

01:22:12.000 --> 01:22:15.300
that he just can't be much
of a contributor anymore.

01:22:15.300 --> 01:22:19.500
So, he comes back for couple
weeks later but he's mostly gone

01:22:19.500 --> 01:22:21.880
after that-- maybe a
week after the speech.

01:22:21.880 --> 01:22:27.750
So, I see it as much more what
Hamilton really would have liked.

01:22:27.750 --> 01:22:33.910
For Madison, I think it was a
mistake, he may have been sort

01:22:33.910 --> 01:22:37.110
of peeved, as Maria suggested.

01:22:37.110 --> 01:22:40.310
It's wonderful in his
notes he says what--

01:22:40.310 --> 01:22:43.390
and it's sort of embarrassing,
I shouldn't say wonderful.

01:22:43.390 --> 01:22:46.710
He says, "Well Dr.
McClurg recommended it."

01:22:46.710 --> 01:22:50.590 position:56%
Who was a very obscure member of
the Virginia delegation and I wanted

01:22:50.590 --> 01:22:53.060
to sort of support Dr. McClurg.

01:22:53.060 --> 01:22:56.590
And he makes a big point that
Washington did not support it

01:22:56.590 --> 01:22:57.890
in order to protect Washington.

01:22:57.890 --> 01:23:01.750
This is in, you know, he's
writing the notes years later.

01:23:02.810 --> 01:23:10.720
But I think in that moment,
he goofed, he made a mistake.

01:23:10.720 --> 01:23:20.000
And that's much more how
I'm inclined to read it.

