01:23:44.560 --> 01:23:48.930
of the arguments of
original interpretation

01:23:48.930 --> 01:23:54.190
versus the constitution being
a living breathing document?

01:23:54.190 --> 01:23:56.890
&gt;&gt; Mary Sarah Bilder: You
know, I think one of the things

01:23:56.890 --> 01:24:02.730 position:56%
that probably interests a lot people
who've worked on this is you--

01:24:02.730 --> 01:24:08.600 position:56%
is at the very moment they finished
the constitution, they already began

01:24:08.600 --> 01:24:10.430
to disagree over what it meant.

01:24:10.430 --> 01:24:13.290
So, I believe there is no moment

01:24:13.290 --> 01:24:16.330
when the constitution
is not contested.

01:24:16.330 --> 01:24:20.400
The debates over ratification
were basically different ways

01:24:20.400 --> 01:24:22.810
of reading the constitution.

01:24:22.810 --> 01:24:25.450
And Madison was fascinated in this.

01:24:25.450 --> 01:24:29.440 position:56%
There's a great debate in the very
beginning of the very first Congress

01:24:29.440 --> 01:24:32.470
over the question since
the Senate has

01:24:32.470 --> 01:24:35.530
to prove the presidential
appointments,

01:24:35.530 --> 01:24:37.790
how do you remove presidential
appointments?

01:24:37.790 --> 01:24:39.390
Does the Senate get
involved in that?

01:24:39.390 --> 01:24:42.430 position:56%
Or does the president-- it's
something called the removal debate.

01:24:42.430 --> 01:24:46.550
And Madison writes letter
after letter to people.

01:24:46.550 --> 01:24:50.690
This is great and wonderful and
the document doesn't say anything

01:24:50.690 --> 01:24:54.220 position:56%
and there's these four positions and
how are we going to figure it out.

01:24:54.220 --> 01:24:56.570
And so, I think-- and at the time

01:24:56.570 --> 01:25:00.040
in the first Congress some
people argue they ought

01:25:00.040 --> 01:25:02.260
to follow what the people
of the convention said.

01:25:02.260 --> 01:25:05.460
And actually, most of the people
of the convention say, "No,

01:25:05.460 --> 01:25:07.960
don't follow what we said,
let's think this through,"

01:25:07.960 --> 01:25:10.250
because the document
is already ambiguous.

01:25:10.250 --> 01:25:17.620
So, I think my own view is that
they built a document deliberately

01:25:17.620 --> 01:25:22.610
broadly so that it would have
more power than the articles

01:25:22.610 --> 01:25:24.510
of confederation which
had written itself

01:25:24.510 --> 01:25:27.180
out of existence within
the first decade.

01:25:27.180 --> 01:25:29.160
So, that would be my own view.

01:25:29.160 --> 01:25:32.100
I don't know what David's
going to say.

01:25:32.100 --> 01:25:34.680
&gt;&gt; David O. Stewart: Well,
